    <main>
        <section id="culture" class="bg-light">
            <div class="container">
                <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Our Culture</h2>
                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8 mx-auto">
                        <p>The culture of the GPIS is built on a horizontal structure and strong mutual trust. All team members, including leadership, operate as equals, fostering an environment where every contribution is valued and respected. This non-hierarchical approach encourages autonomy and ensures that all voices are heard.</p>
                        <p>The group's daily work is guided by two core principles: social impact and constant innovation. We are not only concerned with producing scientific research but also with its real-world application and its potential to improve population health. Our goal is to avoid stagnation and continually explore new and better ways of conducting research, from methodology to data analysis.</p>
                        <p>The working atmosphere is highly collaborative. While some members are more proactive than others, the team is generally aligned and works together toward shared goals. The participation of all members, regardless of their level of engagement, is welcome and appreciated.</p>
                        <p>A key challenge is fostering a learning environment for students. While we aim to create a space where students feel free to speak and think, we acknowledge that we still need to improve in this area. We lack the dedicated time and expertise to provide extensive mentorship.</p>
                        <p>The long-term vision for the GPIS is to become a leading, well-funded research group. We aspire to manage large-scale projects and secure enough funding to make research the primary job for all members. This would allow each team member to pursue their specific research interests and contribute to the group's overall mission.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="projects">
            <div class="container">
                <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Our Projects</h2>
                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8 mx-auto">
                        <h3>Primary Project: 2019 Rio Grande Birth Cohort</h3>
                        <p>A fixed, prospective, population-based cohort study from a middle-income country, designed to investigate the life course epidemiology of mental health and its intergenerational transmission. The study includes 2,051 mothers and their infants born in Rio Grande in 2019.</p>
                        <p><strong>Key Findings:</strong> The study found a significant increase in maternal mental health problems during the COVID-19 pandemic, with a six-fold increase in depressive symptoms and a three-fold increase in anxiety compared to the baseline.</p>
                        <p><strong>Subprojects:</strong> The cohort study has multiple subprojects, including those that:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Use wearable cameras and AI-powered facial recognition to analyze mother-child interactions.</li>
                            <li>Evaluate the effects of the 2024 floods in Rio Grande do Sul on maternal and child mental health.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p><strong>Key Collaborators:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Rebecca Pearson:</strong> Manchester Metropolitan University (MMU), leader of MHINT. Expert in observational and computational methods.</li>
                            <li><strong>Ana Luiza Goncalves Soares:</strong> University of Bristol. Expert in life course epidemiology and advanced longitudinal analyses.</li>
                            <li><strong>Marc Bornstein:</strong> Eunice Kennedy Shriver National Institute of Child Health and Human Development. Expert in child development and family studies.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="kpis" class="bg-light">
            <div class="container">
                <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)</h2>
                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8 mx-auto">
                        <p><strong>Publications:</strong> We measure success by the number and quality of our scientific publications, with a strong emphasis on publishing in high-impact factor journals. Our priority is quality over quantity.</p>
                        <p><strong>Funding:</strong> We target national funding from CNPq and, internationally, we target grants from organizations like Wellcome. The goal is to secure funding that can support the team members as their main professional activity.</p>
                        <p><strong>Capacity Building (Future KPI):</strong> We do not currently have a formal system to track the professional growth of our students and early-career researchers. However, a key future KPI is to track their progress, including presentations at conferences and the successful completion of their theses.</p>
                        <p><strong>Social Impact (Future KPI):</strong> We do not currently have data to measure our social impact, such as media appearances or community presentations. A future KPI is to implement a system for tracking this and to translate our scientific knowledge into a more broadly accessible format for the public.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

